[[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] '''Sir Edward Blakeney''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|GCB|GCH|PCi}} (26 March 1778 – 2 August 1868) was a [[British Army]] officer. After serving as a junior officer with the [[Dutch colonisation of the Guianas|expedition to Dutch Guiana]] and being taken prisoner by [[privateer]]s three times suffering great hardship, he took part in the [[Anglo-Russian invasion of Holland]] in 1799. He also joined the expedition to [[Denmark]] led by [[William Cathcart, 1st Earl Cathcart|Lord Cathcart]] in 1807. He went on to command the 2nd Battalion of the [[Royal Fusiliers|7th Regiment of Foot]] and then both battalions of that regiment at many of the battles of the [[Peninsular War]]. After joining the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Duke of Wellington]] as he marched into [[Paris]] in 1815, Blakeney fought in the [[War of 1812]]. He then commanded a brigade in the army sent on a mission to Portugal to support the constitutional government against the absolutist forces of [[Miguel I of Portugal|Dom Miguel]] in 1826. His last major appointment was as [[Commander-in-Chief, Ireland]], a post he held for nearly twenty years.

==Early life==
Born the fourth son of Colonel [[William Blakeney (died 1804)|William Blakeney]] and Sarah Blakeney (née Shields), Blakeney was commissioned as a [[Cornet (military rank)|cornet]] in the [[8th King's Royal Irish Hussars|8th Light Dragoons]] on 28 February 1794.<ref name=odnb>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/2589|title=Sir Edward Blakeney|publisher=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> He was promoted to [[lieutenant]] in the [[121st Regiment of Foot (1794)|121st Regiment of Foot]] on 4 September 1794 and to [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in the [[99th Regiment of Foot (1794)|99th Regiment of Foot]] on 24 December 1794.<ref name=heath46>Heathcote, p. 46</ref> He took part in the [[Dutch colonisation of the Guianas|expedition to Dutch Guiana]] in 1796 and was taken prisoner by [[privateer]]s three times suffering great hardship.<ref name=heath46/> He also took part in the evacuation of [[Santo Domingo]] in 1798.<ref name = "Dod">Dod, pp. 120–121</ref>

Blakeney transferred to the [[Royal Leicestershire Regiment|17th Regiment of Foot]] on 10 March 1798<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=14096|supp=|startpage=203|date=6 March 1798|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> and saw action at the [[Battle of Krabbendam]] and the [[Battle of Bergen (1799)|Battle of Bergen]] both in September 1799 and the [[Battle of Alkmaar (1799)|Battle of Alkmaar]] and the [[Battle of Castricum]] both in October 1799 during the [[Anglo-Russian invasion of Holland]].<ref name=heath46/> Promoted to [[major]] on 17 September 1801, he transferred to the [[47th (Lancashire) Regiment of Foot|47th Regiment of Foot]] on 11 July 1803.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=15600|supp=|startpage=830|date=9 July 1803|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> After transferring again, this time to the [[Royal Fusiliers|7th Regiment of Foot]] on 7 April 1804,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=15689|supp=|startpage=408|date=3 April 1804|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> he joined the expedition to [[Denmark]] led by [[William Cathcart, 1st Earl Cathcart|Lord Cathcart]], took part in the  [[Battle of Copenhagen (1807)|Battle of Copenhagen]] in August 1807 and, having been promoted to [[lieutenant colonel]] on 7 May 1808,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=16142|supp=|startpage=623|date=3 May 1808|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> also took part in the capture of [[Martinique]] in February 1809.<ref name=heath46/> He undertook garrison duty in [[Nova Scotia]] later that year.<ref name=heath47>Heathcote, p. 47</ref>

==Peninsular War==
Blakeney joined [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Sir Arthur Wellesley]] in Spain in June 1810 and commanded the 2nd Battalion of his regiment during the [[Battle of Bussaco]] in September 1810 and the [[Battle of Albuera]] (where he was severely wounded in the thigh) in May 1811.<ref name=heath47/> He commanded both battalions of his regiment at the Combat of Aldea da Ponte in September 1811, at the [[Siege of Ciudad Rodrigo (1812)|Siege of Ciudad Rodrigo]] in January 1812 and at the [[Siege of Badajoz (1812)|Siege of Badajoz]] (where he was severely wounded through the arm in the assault) in April 1812.<ref name=heath47/> He also commanded at the [[Battle of Vitoria]] in June 1813, at the Combat of Pampelona in June 1813 and at the [[Battle of the Pyrenees]] in July 1813 as well as the [[Battle of Nivelle]] in November 1813.<ref name=heath47/> Promoted to [[colonel]] on 4 June 1814<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=16906|supp=|startpage=1182|date=7 June 1814|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> and appointed a [[Order of the Bath|Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] on 2 January 1815, he fought at the [[Battle of New Orleans]] in January 1815 during the [[War of 1812]].<ref name=heath47/> Although he did not take part in the [[Hundred Days]], he joined the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Duke of Wellington]] as he marched into [[Paris]] in 1815 and served with the Army of Occupation in France until 1819.<ref name=heath47/>

==Later years==
Promoted to [[major general]] on 27 May 1825,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=18141|supp=|startpage=925|date=28 May 1825|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref>  Blakeney commanded a brigade in the army under General [[Henry Clinton (Napoleonic Wars)|Henry Clinton]] sent on a mission to Portugal to support the constitutional government against the absolutist forces of [[Miguel I of Portugal|Dom Miguel]] in 1826.<ref name=heath47/>

Blakeney went on to become [[Commander-in-Chief, Ireland]] in Spring 1836 at a time when the deaths and starvation in [[Ireland]] caused by the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]] were giving rise to civil unrest and the need to use coercion to maintain order.<ref>Saville, p. 156</ref> He was appointed a [[Lord Justices (Ireland)|Lord Justice of Ireland]] on 7 May 1836<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19383|supp=|startpage=867|date=17 May 1836|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> and promoted to the local rank of [[lieutenant-general]] on 26 August 1836<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19420|supp=|startpage=1617|date=16 September 1836|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> and to the substantive rank of lieutenant-general on 28 June 1838.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19631|supp=|startpage=1489|date=3 July 1838|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> He was advanced to [[Order of the Bath|Knight Grand Cross of the Bath]] on 7 May 1849<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=20977|supp=|startpage=1552|date=11 May 1849|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> and, having been promoted to full [[general]] on 20 June 1854,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=21564|supp=|startpage=1931|date=22 June 1854|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> retired from active service in 1855.<ref name=heath47/>

Blakeney also served as honorary colonel of the 7th Regiment of Foot,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=18979|supp=|startpage=2145|date=25 September 1832|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> then as honorary colonel of the [[Royal Scots|1st Regiment of Foot]]<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=21647|supp=|startpage=1|date=2 January 1855|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> and later as colonel-in-chief of the [[Rifle Brigade (Prince Consort's Own)|Rifle Brigade]]<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=23015|supp=|startpage=4510|date=19 September 1865|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> as well as honorary colonel of the St. George's Rifle Volunteer Corps.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=23372|supp=|startpage=2304|date=21 April 1868|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> He became lieutenant-governor of the [[Royal Hospital Chelsea]] on 6 February 1855<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=21658|supp=|startpage=431|date=6 February 1855|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> and then succeeded as Governor of that establishment on 25 September 1856.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=98501#s2 |title=Survey of London, volume 11|first= Walter H.|last=Godfrey|year= 1927|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref>

In retirement Blakeney lived at [[Richmond House, Twickenham|Richmond House]] in [[Twickenham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoriesoftwickenhamriverside.com/richmond.html|title=Richmond House|publisher=Memories of Twickenham Riverside|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> Promoted to [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|field marshal]] on 9 November 1862,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=22679|supp=|startpage=5343|date=10 November 1862|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> he died at the Royal Hospital Chelsea on 2 August 1868 and was buried at Oak Lane Cemetery in Twickenham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=29773974|title=Edward Blakeney|publisher=Find a grave|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref>

==Family==
In 1814 Blakeney married Maria Gardiner, a daughter of Colonel Gardiner of the [[East India Company]]; they had no children.<ref name=heath47/>
